cs.SI, cs.IR, cs.CY, cs.MM, cs.SOC

This paper likely belongs to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) because it examines the role of YouTube's recommendation algorithm in promoting or discouraging radicalized content. It may also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) because the study involves analyzing recommendation traffic flows between different types of political channels. Additionally, it could fall under cs.CY (Computers and Society) because it addresses the societal impact of algorithmic recommendations on online radicalization. The paper may also be relevant to cs.MM (Multimedia) because it involves analyzing video content on YouTube, and cs.SOC (Social and Community Informatics) because it examines the impact of online communities and networks on radicalization.
